[{"id":"VR864797","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Show all your work for each part of the question. The parts within the question may not have equal weight.</p><br/><div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 1 shows a nonuniform bar attached to a wall by a fixed pivot at its left end, and the bar is held horizontal by a string attached to the bar and to the wall at a point above the pivot. The bar has length L. The string is attached to the bar at a distance L over 3 from the pivot. The bar’s center of mass is a distance L over 3 from the bar’s free end.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR864797.g09.svg\"/></div>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">A nonuniform bar is attached to a wall by a fixed pivot at its left end, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>. The bar has length <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L\"><math alttext=\"L\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>L</mi></math></span></span> and mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\"><math alttext=\"M\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>M</mi></math></span></span>. Its mass is distributed such that the bar’s center of mass is a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L over 3\"><math alttext=\"L over 3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mi>L</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math></span></span> from the bar’s free end and the bar’s rotational inertia about the pivot is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"one half M L squared\"><math alttext=\"one half M L squared\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>M</mi><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mstyle></math></span></span>. A string is attached to the wall and to the bar as shown, holding the bar horizontal.</p>\n</div></div></div></div><div class=\"item_part part_id:A part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"A\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The bar is shown again in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, and the dots in the figure are located at the point of attachment for the string and at the bar’s center of mass.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) In Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">draw</span> and <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">label</span> arrows that represent the forces (not components) that are exerted on the bar. Each force must be represented by a distinct arrow starting on, and pointing away from, the point at which the force is exerted on the bar.</p><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 2 shows the bar from Figure 1 with two points indicated. The first point is a third of the way from the left end and at the top of the bar. The second point is two thirds from the left end and in the interior of the bar.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR864797.g06.svg\"/></div></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR864797_rubric"},{"id":"VR864797","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The string is cut, and the bar starts rotating from its initially horizontal position. As the bar rotates, a constant frictional torque of magnitude <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the fraction 1 over 12, end fraction, times M g L\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"the fraction 1 over 12, end fraction, times M g L\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>12</mn></mfrac><mi>M</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>L</mi></math></span></span> is exerted on the bar by the pivot.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) Starting with Newton’s second law in rotational form, derive an expression for the bar’s angular acceleration immediately after the string is cut, when the bar has started to rotate but is still approximately horizontal. Express your answer in terms of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"L\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>L</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"M\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>M</mi></math></span></span>, and physical constants, as appropriate. Begin your derivation by writing either a fundamental physics principle or an equation from the reference book.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR864797_rubric"},{"id":"VR864797","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:C part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"C\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) On the axes in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>, <b>sketch&nbsp;</b>a graph of the angular acceleration of the bar as a function of the angle between the bar and the horizontal. Take the positive direction to be clockwise. On the vertical axis in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"alpha sub b\"><math alttext=\"alpha sub b\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>α</mi><mtext>b</mtext></msub></math></span></span> is the magnitude of the angular acceleration derived in part (b).</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 3 shows the first and fourth quadrants of a coordinate grid. The horizontal axis is labeled “Angle from Horizontal,” and the values 0 degrees and 90 degrees are indicated. Zero degrees corresponds to the vertical axis, and a dashed vertical grid line is drawn through the plane at 90 degrees. The vertical axis is labeled “Angular Acceleration,” and the values negative alpha sub b, 0, and alpha sub b are indicated. Zero corresponds to the horizontal axis, and dashed horizontal grid lines are drawn through the plane at negative alpha sub b and alpha sub b.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR864797.g11.svg\" /></div>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR864797_rubric"},{"id":"VR864797","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:D part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"D\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 4 shows a nonuniform bar attached to a wall by a fixed pivot at its left end, and the bar is held horizontal by a string attached to the wall and to the bar. The bar has length L. The point of attachment for the string and the bar’s center of mass are both a distance L over 3 from the bar’s free end.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR864797.g12.svg\"/></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The bar is returned to the horizontal position. Another string is then attached to the bar, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"4\"><math alttext=\"4\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>4</mn></math></span></span>. This time, the string is attached to the bar so that it is lined up with the bar’s center of mass. The string is also attached to a higher location on the wall so that it is oriented at the same angle as the original string.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) Other than the force exerted by the string, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">indicate</span> how a force represented in the diagram you drew for part (a) would change, if at all, with the second string attached to the bar and wall as in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"4\"><math alttext=\"4\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>4</mn></math></span></span>. If there would be no changes to any other forces, state this explicitly. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Justify</span> your answer.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR864797_rubric"}]